@RW

Well, it’s not necessarily a fallacy, it’s a real thing. But I suppose it’s a fallacy to be assume it should be applied rigidly. So if you want to tax sodas higher because they are unhealthy, someone may oppose that and say it’s a slippery slope—perhaps we will start taxing meat or eggs or candy higher because we say that’s unhealthy too. And the original proponent might say, that’s a fallacy, just because we tax sodas doesn’t mean we will start taxing everything else. 

But of course a slippery slope may happen in that case so it just depends what end of the stick you are on

@yc

