@Barry Ancona

I think Joseph is talking about the night that some of the squares had break dancers forming letters.  

I know I had a lot of trouble that night.

@jp inflaming

You're not really supposed to read the column before you solve.  The idea is to use the visuals and clues in the puzzle to figure out what's going on.

It helps to just relax and know that as you solve, the trick will reveal itself.  Try not to get frustrated early on when answers don't make sense, and just press on until you get it.

@jp inframan

I might add to Nancy J.'s comment, that sometimes if you think you have an answer, you just plop it in, and see if any of the crosses come to light with that entry.  If you get one, or better two, that's a pretty good sign the answer is right.

If not, you mentally mark that entry as a possible error.

@SBK  @Matt

Thanks for this discussion! Despite enjoying watching the NHL (for decades), I had zero idea of what this piece of arcana would solve to, and was grateful for the (over-easy) crosses. A ship reference would have been so much better! Even if, having only ever heard it (in films and TV), I probably would've spelled it with only one N... 

NB, this is a glaring example of the current era of NYTXD cluing. It's so uneven! Why choose an extra-obscure reference just to make up for overly straightforward clues elsewhere? At least that's how it feels to me... 🤷‍♀️

