@Calig
I agree.  It would never occur to me that I couldn't do a puzzle!

I will say, at times we quail before realizing something is not as daunting as we fear.  I thought of that when "GRE" was in the puzzle recently.  When I took it, there was a section on "Sentence Completion."  The first item was on a physics topic--and my heart sank; but then I realized all I really had to do was understand the grammar and syntax of the complex sentences--not the content.  Bingo.

@Calig
I figured out what the symbols meant by looking at my finished grid, so I have no complaint. I learned something new and enjoyed it. 

But I'm curious how you knew the symbols if you've never been downhill skiing? From friends, maybe? I have watched Olympic skiing competitions on TV but don't remember ever seeing those signs. Kind of makes sense competition slopes wouldn't have them, at least not the colors.

@Down_Home
I’m always so impressed when people are able to make a graceful apology and even include a compliment. Too rare these days. 
Well done!

@miniMeissner
Thanks for the clarification. 
Makes A lot of sense

@Karen
I also have a traumatic memory of downhill skiing. I was with a significant other who had a flawed theory of how to teach skiing.  Let's leave it at that.

It did convince me that my ankles are way too flexible to keep a ski straight. Going cross-country in other people's grooves is more my style.

@MartyS, I can understand your view of skiing as a sport accessible only to the wealthy. The giant luxury resorts, designer gear, and more do support that conclusion.

But that's not true everywhere, and most people I know who ski don't stay at the fancy resorts. They stay nearby in regular hotels/motels with their kids. They ski for long weekends, or during (here in New England) February school break.

I'm not saying skiing isn't expensive; it is. But there are ways for ordinary people to ski and not break the bank.

@Joe F.
Since I don't hang out with 1%ers, you may be right. The only people I know who downhill ski regularly are at least upper middle class. 

But I am probably biased. I don't go to amusement parks, either. If I'm going to spend money on amusements, I do it in my own snobbish way--on winter camping gear and National Park passes. I justify the winter gear by telling myself that if we have an extended power outage, I'm gonna be smug, uh snug. Snug.

@Joe F. 
And before anyone says anything, I know National Parks are closed in the winter. But I have camped with my aged parents in the snow in a Massachusetts state park.

Anyway, even if I can't use the money excuse to avoid downhill, I'll find some other excuse.

@Francis

Completely agree it depends on how much money is in the bank.

I think I was well into adulthood before I stayed in a motel. But we had gas money to travel and camp, and my parents pointed out that many of my classmates did not and probably never would.

@MartyS We have a ski hill about 45 minutes drive from Halifax, Nova Scotia. The season’s passes, December to April are $200 for an adult, $120 for kids, with discounts you can apply for. They have a gear swap every year. 

I learned to ski on a ravine slope in Toronto that had a rope tow, and it was $5 an afternoon - a long time ago, but still …

You don’t have to be upper-middle-class or wealthy to ski. It has an unwarranted reputation for being elitist and unaffordable. My kids and I enjoyed it for much less money.
